Partial Dependence Profiles and Accumulated Local Dependence for explaining models on the Titanic dataset¶

author: Witalis Domitrz witekdomitrz@gmail.com

The first model well presents the importance of the age - the children were generally much more likely to survive. The most likely to survive were the newborns, then the possibility goes down for children that were not with their mothers all the time and raises a little bit as the children became more mature. Then there is a huge difference of more than 0.45 percent between the children and adults. The model also points that the younger adults are more likely to survive then those older than 38 years old. There are some minor fluctuations that might be a good point for the future investigation. The fare profile is also quite interesting. We see very unstable profile for the lower fare - it might be caused by some over fitting. It might be a good idea to try mark the fare as a range (eg. fare between 0 and 5, between 5 and 20 etc.). There is also an interesting fenomena that the probability of the survival is smaller in a fare range between 120 and 250 that I don't fully understand - it might be the price range for the adults in the second class. The lower fare for the children might have caused the instability of low fare profile and the high fare profile probably represents the passengers from the first class.

The random forest and k-nearest neighbours models present similar, but a little bit smoother profile of the age - the children are most likely to survive and the older the adults, the lower the probability of survival. Both plots presents similar tendency and their fits the models behaviours. The profile of the age for decision tree presents some strange anomalies - the huge drop for the ~10 years old children, than back again high possibility of survival. It might be a flaw in the model, which is quite good guess, especially when comparing it with the profiles of models with higher accuracy. The SGD model seems to have much different profile than the others and it might be caused by the low capacity of the model, which was unable to model interactions between variables. For the fare situation with SGD is similar which even more causes doubts about the model's relevance. The profiles of the fare for random forest and decision tree present similar tendencies with visible point of high probability of survival in one point (which we see at a glance for the decision tree, but it is also visible for the random forest). The interesting thing is that the k-nearest neighbours model presents similar tendency to the XGB model - much lower survival probability for a range of fare from 150 up to 250.

import numpy as np
import pandas as pd

used_columns = ['Pclass', 'Sex', 'Age', 'SibSp', 'Parch', 'Fare', 'Embarked', 'Survived']
X_columns = ['Pclass', 'Age', 'SibSp', 'Parch', 'Fare', 'Sex_male', 'Embarked_C', 'Embarked_Q', 'Embarked_S']
Y_columns = ['Survived']

def load_data(fn):
    return pd.read_csv(fn).set_index('PassengerId')

def to_array(data):
    return pd.get_dummies(data).astype(dtype='float32')

def data_preprocessing():
    global train, test
    train = load_data('./train.csv')
    test = load_data('./gender_submission.csv').join(load_data('./test.csv'))  

    train['is_train'] = True
    test['is_train'] = False
    data = pd.concat([train, test])

    # Replace missing values with mean
    data.fillna(data.mean(), inplace=True)

    # Split test and train
    train, test = data[data['is_train']], data[data['is_train'] == False]

    # No unused columns
    train, test = train[used_columns], test[used_columns]

    train, test = to_array(train), to_array(test)
data_preprocessing()


def split_to_x_y(data):
    return to_array(data[X_columns]), to_array(data[Y_columns])

def get_data():
    return split_to_x_y(train), split_to_x_y(test)

def unlabel_data(*sets):
    return ((part.values for part in subset) for subset in sets)

(train_x, train_y), (test_x, test_y) = get_data()

Function to check a model accuracy¶

In [0]:
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score
def check_accuracy(model, xy=(test_x, test_y)):
    x, y = xy
    pred = model.predict(x)
    accuracy = accuracy_score(y, [round(value) for value in pred])
    return accuracy

2.¶

for selected variables from the model (1) calculate Partial Dependence Profiles and Accumulated Local Dependence

Use dalex¶

In [0]:
from dalex import Explainer
In [0]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
SELECTED_VARIABLES_DEFAULT = ['Age', 'Fare']
def show_acc_pdp_and_ale(model_name, model, xy=(test_x, test_y), selected_variables=SELECTED_VARIABLES_DEFAULT, **kwargs):
    
    print("model:", model_name, "\taccuracy:", check_accuracy(model, xy=xy))
    
    x, y = xy

    explainer = Explainer(model=model, data=x, y=y.values[::, 0], model_type='classifier')

    pdp = explainer.model_profile(type='partial', variables=selected_variables)
    pdp.plot(title=model_name + ": Partial Dependence Profiles")

    ale = explainer.model_profile(type='accumulated', variables=selected_variables)
    ale.plot(title=model_name + ": Accumulated Local Dependence")
